---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import FoundationPager from '../../components/FoundationPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'The five-layer stack';
const description =
  'Every piece of context an agent reads belongs in exactly one layer: System, Project, Codebase, Session, Tooling. Mixing them is the most common failure in AI-assisted engineering.';
---

<Doc title={title} description={description} section="foundation" eyebrow="Foundation · 01">
  <p class="doc-lede">
    Every piece of information an AI agent reads belongs in exactly one of
    five layers. Mixing them is the single most common cause of "the agent did
    the right thing locally and broke conventions globally".
  </p>

  <h2>The five layers</h2>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Layer</th><th>What lives here</th><th>Persistence</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>System</strong></td>
        <td>Role, persona, hard guardrails, output-format constraints</td>
        <td>High · static</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Project</strong></td>
        <td>Repo-level rules and conventions everyone shares</td>
        <td>Medium · versioned</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Codebase</strong></td>
        <td>Deep awareness of the actual code — indices, repo maps, on-demand reads</td>
        <td>Medium · dynamic</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Session</strong></td>
        <td>The state of the task right now — chat history, recent tool output, the file just opened</td>
        <td>Low · transient</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Tooling</strong></td>
        <td>What the agent can do — MCP servers, CLI permissions, API definitions</td>
        <td>Medium · infrastructure</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Why mixing layers breaks things</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>
      A naming convention written in the <strong>Session</strong> layer is
      gone the moment the session ends. Put it in <strong>Project</strong> and
      every future agent inherits it.
    </li>
    <li>
      A timezone assumption baked into <strong>Project</strong> ("the server
      is UTC") is wrong for the user running locally in CET. Put it in
      <strong>Session</strong> so the agent asks instead.
    </li>
    <li>
      Product docs in the <strong>System</strong> layer waste tokens on every
      call and push real instructions out of the model's immediate attention.
      Reference them from the <strong>Codebase</strong> layer; load on demand.
    </li>
    <li>
      Database credentials in <strong>Project</strong> get committed to git.
      They belong in <strong>Tooling</strong> — scoped to an MCP server the
      agent can call but cannot read.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The decision tree</h2>

  <p>When you are about to write a rule somewhere, ask:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Does it apply to every interaction in every repo?</strong> → System.</li>
    <li><strong>Does it apply to every task in this repo, no matter who is doing it?</strong> → Project.</li>
    <li><strong>Is it something the agent needs to look up about the actual code?</strong> → Codebase. Do not write it down statically; reference where to find it.</li>
    <li><strong>Is it only true for the current task or the current user's machine?</strong> → Session.</li>
    <li><strong>Is it about what the agent is allowed to do or how it talks to other systems?</strong> → Tooling.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    If a rule fits two layers, it almost always means the rule is too big and
    should be split.
  </p>

  <h2>What good looks like</h2>

  <p>
    A <code>CLAUDE.md</code> (Project layer) that says, in three sentences:
  </p>
  <pre><code>We use pnpm, not npm. Tests run with `pnpm test`. Lint with `pnpm lint`.
For Python tooling see `pyproject.toml`. For deploy steps see `docs/deploy.md`.</code></pre>

  <p>
    That is three sentences. It names the static facts, points to where the
    dynamic facts live, and names the verification commands. Everything else
    lives in its own layer.
  </p>
  <p>
    A <code>CLAUDE.md</code> that runs to 800 lines describing the product,
    customer personas, and every architectural decision ever made has failed.
    Those belong in dedicated docs that the Codebase layer points to.
  </p>

  <Callout label="In practice" tone="ember">
    <p>
      <a href={url('commands/init/')}><code>init</code></a> and
      <a href={url('commands/document/')}><code>document</code></a> set up the
      Project layer.
      <a href={url('commands/scope/')}><code>scope</code></a> subdivides it
      where directories diverge.
      <a href={url('commands/mcp/')}><code>mcp</code></a> sets up the Tooling
      layer.
      <a href={url('commands/audit/')}><code>audit</code></a> scores every
      layer independently.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <p>
    Source: <a href={url('blueprint/#five-layer')}>2026 Context Engineering
    Blueprint — The Five-Layer Context Stack</a>.
  </p>

  <FoundationPager slug="five-layer-stack" />
</Doc>
